==English==

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɒrɪk|-ɒrɪk]]

===Adjective===
'''historic'''
# having [[importance]] or [[significance]] in [[history]]
# belonging to the [[past]]; [[historical]]

===Note===

Sentences involving the word "historic" sometimes use "a historic" and sometimes use "an historic".  This has something to do with British English versus American English, and should be expanded in this article. 
===Usage note===
Some native-speakers maintain a distinction between '''historic''' and '''historical'''. '''Historic''' pertains to an actual event of history, while '''historical''' pertains to history and history-telling. 
#:''July 4, 1776 is a historic date. A great deal of historical research has been done on the events leading up to that day.''
#:''The historical works of Lord Macaulay and Edward Gibbon are in and of themselves historic.''

